# 2026-04-11-justfile



## J is for Justfile

My coworker put me on to justfile a bit ago, and after wrestling with Makefiles for a few decades, its a nice upgrade.

The justfile syntax is yaml with instructions that are in yaml for more credence towards earning my greatest title of 'yaml developer'.
Not the biggest fan of using more yaml, all jokes aside, toml has been my goto recently, however that aside, its got some solid QoL built in.
I haven't gotten any "missing separator" errors, and parameter passing uses {{variable}} syntax which does not require memorizing recursive
expansion gotchas (been spending alot of time with golang style templating, so its a nice break in syntax) or escaping dollars with double $$ symbols.

But all that said, justfile, makefiles, or my old fav Taskfiles (used them alot with my golang stacks and scala). It really comes down to technique.

So run away now if you don't want to hear a rant.

## Normalizing projects

IMHO its a huge benefit to projects personal or professional to always have a 'make' or equivelent. Im digging the just syntax but I wanted to be clear. The technique
is that projects should allow for the following:

* just build
* just test
* just lint

Thats it, then when using Dockerfiles, I include make or just and use those commands as well. That keeps the high level targets of a project always center stage.
Plus, its just nice to know that whatever repo im in I can count on those commands being around.

Anyhow, thats it for today, cheers!


